<% content_for(:title, "notifications") %>

<%# Phase 16 §3 — Notification inbox.
    UX restructure 2026-05-10:
      - Filter row is now a `[ ] unread` checkbox (FilterChipComponent,
        `param: "filter"`, `value: "unread"`) plus a dynamic
        `[mark all as read]` / `[mark <N> as read]` button.
      - The bulk-select pattern (channels / videos / projects) wraps
        the table — first column is a row checkbox, only rendered for
        unread rows.
      - The notification detail opens in an in-page modal via the
        `notification-modal` Stimulus controller. The `<dialog>` and
        its inner Turbo Frame live at the bottom of the page so every
        row click reuses the same surface. The `/notifications/:id`
        route stays as a fallback for direct links and JS-off paths.
      - A muted caption under the H1 explains the cleanup behaviour
        ("notifications are deleted 7 days after being read.") so
        the cron job's data loss is discoverable.

    Inbox layout revamp 2026-05-11 (per user direction):
      - The table now carries an explicit `<thead>` with five labelled
        columns: `select`, `kind`, `title`, `severity`, `when`. Matches
        the `<thead><th>…</th></thead>` pattern used app-wide
        (videos / channels / settings tokens / sessions).
      - The per-event-type emoji legend that previously rendered as a
        single muted comma-separated caption at the TOP of the page is
        now at the BOTTOM (after the table + pagination, before the
        notification-detail modal) laid out as a two-column grid with
        one `<emoji> <kind label>` pair per line — easier to scan once
        you've already seen the table and need to decode an icon.

    Index live-prepends new rows via `notifications_index` Turbo
    Stream subscription; the badge updates via the separate
    `notifications_badge` stream.

    Layout-level modal mode (2026-05-10): when `@modal` is set (the
    controller flips it on `?modal=yes` or a matching `Turbo-Frame`
    header), the body is wrapped in
    `<turbo-frame id="notifications_modal_frame">` so the layout-level
    `shared/_notifications_modal` dialog can pull the inbox into its
    frame via `src=`. Outside modal mode neither open nor close tag is
    emitted, so the standalone `/notifications` page keeps its exact
    previous DOM — every existing index spec asserts against the same
    shape it did before this change. %>
<%= turbo_stream_from "notifications_index" %>

<% if @modal %><turbo-frame id="notifications_modal_frame"><% end %>
<div style="max-width: 1100px;"
     data-controller="bulk-select notifications-dynamic-button"
     data-bulk-select-entity-name-value="notifications"
     data-notifications-dynamic-button-mark-all-url-value="<%= mark_all_read_notifications_path %>"
     data-notifications-dynamic-button-mark-read-url-value="<%= mark_read_notifications_path %>"
     data-notifications-dynamic-button-total-unread-value="<%= @unread_count %>">
  <h1>notifications</h1>
  <p class="text-muted" style="margin: 4px 0 8px;">notifications are deleted 7 days after being read.</p>

  <% if @has_failures %>
    <div class="webhook-failure-banner" style="border: 1px solid var(--color-border); padding: 6px 10px; margin: 8px 0; color: var(--color-muted);">
      webhook delivery failing — see notification detail.
    </div>
  <% end %>

  <%# Filter cluster — `[ ] unread` checkbox chip + dynamic mark-as-read
      button. Default (no `filter=unread`) shows all rows; checking the
      chip flips the URL to `?filter=unread` (FilterChipComponent
      handles the toggle). The mark-read button's text + form action
      are managed by `notifications-dynamic-button` Stimulus controller
      (label flips between "mark all as read" and "mark <N> as read",
      action between `mark_all_read` and `mark_read?ids=…`). %>
  <div class="dot-list" style="margin: 8px 0; align-items: baseline;">
    <%# `path: notifications_path` pins the chip's href to an
        ABSOLUTE URL (`/notifications?filter=unread&modal=yes` instead
        of `?filter=unread&modal=yes`). The modal at the layout level
        loads this page inside `notifications_modal_frame` with
        `src=/notifications?modal=yes`; a relative href resolves
        against the document URL (whatever page the modal was opened
        from — e.g. `/channels`), NOT the frame's src. Without the
        absolute pin the chip click navigates to
        `/channels?filter=unread&modal=yes`, which has no matching
        modal frame and Turbo renders "Content missing". %>
    <%= render(FilterChipComponent.new(
          label: "unread",
          param: "filter",
          value: "unread",
          current_params: request.query_parameters,
          path: notifications_path
        )) %>
    <span style="flex: 1;"></span>
    <% if @unread_count > 0 %>
      <%# `data-turbo-frame="_top"` on the form escapes the enclosing
          `notifications_modal_frame` (in modal mode). The endpoint
          redirects back to `notifications_path` on success, which is
          a standalone page WITHOUT the modal frame wrapper — without
          `_top` Turbo would scope the redirect to the modal frame
          and render "Content missing". %>
      <%= form_with url: mark_all_read_notifications_path,
            method: :patch,
            data: { notifications_dynamic_button_target: "form", turbo_frame: "_top" },
            html: { style: "display: inline; margin: 0;" } do %>
        <button type="submit" class="bracketed"
                style="background: none; border: none; padding: 0; font: inherit; color: var(--color-link); cursor: pointer;">[<span class="bl" data-notifications-dynamic-button-target="label">mark all as read</span>]</button>
      <% end %>
    <% end %>
  </div>

  <% if @notifications.empty? && @page == 1 %>
    <p class="text-muted">no notifications yet.</p>
  <% else %>
    <%# Columns:
          select   — bulk-select checkbox (always-on column; the
                     dynamic [ mark N as read ] button filters by
                     `.notification-unread` so a ticked read row is
                     silently ignored).
          kind     — per-event-type emoji glyph from
                     `NotificationFormatter::EVENT_TYPE_EMOJI`. Decoded
                     by the legend at the bottom of the page.
          title    — humanized title (clickable, opens the detail modal).
          severity — `Notification#severity` enum value rendered as a
                     bordered badge. Enum members (see
                     `app/models/notification.rb`): info, success, warn,
                     urgent.
          when     — `payload[:fires_at_relative]` (e.g. "2 hours ago"). %>
    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 13px;">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th class="col-action">select</th>
          <th>kind</th>
          <th>title</th>
          <th>severity</th>
          <th>when</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody id="notifications_list">
        <%= render partial: "notification", collection: @notifications, as: :notification %>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <% if @total_pages > 1 %>
      <div class="dot-list" style="margin-top: 12px;">
        <% if @page > 1 %>
          <%= render(BracketedLinkComponent.new(label: "prev page", href: url_for(page: @page - 1))) %>
        <% end %>
        <span>page <%= @page %> / <%= @total_pages %></span>
        <% if @page < @total_pages %>
          <%= render(BracketedLinkComponent.new(label: "next page", href: url_for(page: @page + 1))) %>
        <% end %>
      </div>
    <% end %>
  <% end %>

  <%# Glyph legend (post-table). Each row's `kind` column renders a
      per-event-type emoji (📺, 🎮, 🚨…) sourced from
      `NotificationFormatter::EVENT_TYPE_EMOJI`. The legend below
      decodes the pictographs — one `<glyph> <kind label>` pair per
      registered event type, laid out as a two-column grid with one
      pair per line. Rebuilt from the formatter constant at render-time
      so a new kind landing in the map appears here automatically.
      Severity (the bordered badge in its own column) is self-
      documenting — the badge text IS the enum value — so no legend
      entry is needed for that axis. %>
  <% legend_pairs = NotificationFormatter::EVENT_TYPE_EMOJI.map { |kind, emoji|
       [ emoji, kind.tr("_", " ") ]
     } %>
  <div class="notification-glyph-legend text-muted"
       style="margin: 16px 0 8px; display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 2px 16px; max-width: 480px;">
    <% legend_pairs.each do |emoji, label| %>
      <div class="notification-glyph-legend-item">
        <span class="notification-glyph" aria-hidden="true"><%= emoji %></span>
        <span><%= label %></span>
      </div>
    <% end %>
  </div>

  <%# Notification detail modal. The dialog stays empty on first
      render — the inner Turbo Frame's `src` is set by
      `notification-modal#open` when a row is clicked, which causes
      Turbo to fetch the show page and swap the matching frame. The
      show template wraps its body in `turbo_frame_tag
      "notification_detail_frame"` so the swap targets exactly the
      content we want.

      Closing happens on Escape (native <dialog>), click outside
      (`clickOutside` action on the dialog), or the show page's
      `[ close ]` / `[ back ]` button (also wired to `close`). %>
  <span data-controller="notification-modal">
    <dialog data-notification-modal-target="dialog"
            data-action="click->notification-modal#clickOutside"
            class="pane-dialog notification-modal">
      <div style="padding: 12px 16px; min-width: 480px; max-width: 800px; max-height: 80vh; overflow-y: auto;">
        <%= turbo_frame_tag "notification_detail_frame", data: { notification_modal_target: "frame" } %>
      </div>
    </dialog>
  </span>
</div>
<% if @modal %></turbo-frame><% end %>
